    <text>
        <body>
            <head><name type="stone"><placeName type="townland"
                >Ratass</placeName></name>, Co. <placeName
                    type="county">Kerry</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KE029-157002-"
                >KE029-157002-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Ecclesiastical</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Probable early ecclesiastical site - Romanesque and earlier fabric/elements within the surviving church. 
                        A cross-slab was also found here, which is possibly contemporary with the cross inscribed on the ogham stone
                        (<ref type="bibliog" target="#FAN1977"
                            ><bibl><author>Fanning and Ó Corráin</author>
                                <date when="1977">1977</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >15-6</biblScope></bibl></ref>). Additionally, the first edition Ordnance Survey map shows a 'curved townland
                        boundary aligned on curved field boundaries to the east, west and north of the early church and associated graveyard' 
                        suggesting a possible large (230x140m) early ecclesiastical enclosure around the site (see <ref
                            target="https://www.academia.edu/4404127/A_Parable_of_Parabolas_Graveyards_with_Evidence_for_Early_Enclosure"
                            >Connolly</ref>).</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p><rs type="material"/>Fine purple sandstone, 
                        <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.45</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.34</measure>m x
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth">0.20</measure>m
                            (<ref type="bibliog" target="#FAN1977"
                                ><bibl><author>Fanning and Ó Corráin</author>
                                    <date when="1977">1977</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >14</biblScope></bibl></ref>). </rs>
                    </p>
                    <p><q>On the opposite broad face to the Ogham and placed at the wider end of the pillar stone [upside down in relation to the ogham inscription] 
                        is a simple Latin <rs type="feature">cross</rs> composed of double grooves. 
                        It has closed terminals except at the stem which is open-ended... It is also worthy of note that the dressing on the top of the ogham inscription 
                        is similar to the pocking behind the cross</q> (<ref type="bibliog" target="#FAN1977"
                            ><bibl><author>Fanning and Ó Corráin</author>
                                <date when="1977">1977</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >15</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p>
                     <p>Fanning also notes that the stone went through a phase of being used as <q>a sharpening stone for knives and other blades</q> 
                        with areas of <q>smoothing and polishing together with quite deep scoring</q>.
                         These cuts and marks on the stone are similar to those found on <ref target="search.php?ciic=206">CIIC 206. Kilcoolaght East I</ref>, Co. Kerry; 
                         <ref target="search.php?ciic=Church_Island">Church Island</ref>, Co. Kerry (used for sharpening 'some broad bladed implement'); <ref target="search.php?ciic=19">CIIC 19. 
                             Colbinstown I</ref>, Co. Kildare (described as 'a blade mark'); <ref target="search.php?ciic=57">CIIC 57. Greenhill I</ref>, 
                        Co. Cork, where they have been described as '<rs type="feature">hone scores</rs>' and to another cut on <ref target="search.php?ciic=35">CIIC 35. Tullaherin</ref>, 
                        which Macalister describes as 'an oblique mark of no importance' (see <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#NEW2009"><bibl><author>Newman</author>
                                <date when="2009">2009</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >433-4</biblScope></bibl></ref>). </p>
                   
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>The edge of the stone <q>appears to have been deliberately dressed or shaped and the incisions are clean, regular and unweathered</q> (<ref type="bibliog" target="#FAN1977"
                        ><bibl><author>Fanning and Ó Corráin</author>
                            <date when="1977">1977</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >14</biblScope></bibl></ref>). Fanning suggests that an initial A (giving ANM) was likely <q>obliterated by the chipping and polishing which is very apparant 
                                below the N at this end of the stone</q>. He also suggests that <q>it is possible that another final letter - an A or O giving a genitive form - could 
                                    have been removed</q> from the top of the stone (<ref type="bibliog" target="#FAN1977"
                                        ><bibl><author>Fanning and Ó Corráin</author>
                                            <date when="1977">1977</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                                >14-5</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p>                             
                               
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <w lemma="ANM" type="formula"><supplied reason="lost" cert="high">A</supplied>NM</w>
                        <persName><w lemma="SILLANN">SILLANN</w></persName>
                    <w lemma="MAQI" type="formula">MAQ</w>
                    <persName><w lemma="VATTILLOGG">VATTILLOGG</w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <ab><q>name/insciption of Sílán son of Fáithloga?</q></ab>
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>Ó Corráin (<ref type="bibliog" target="#FAN1977"
                        ><bibl><author>Fanning and Ó Corráin</author>
                            <date when="1977">1977</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >17</biblScope></bibl></ref>) identifies the commemorand as <hi rend="italic">Sílán mac Áedloga</hi> 
                    m. Domungein of the Uí Angáin who, he suggests could be placed in the eight or early ninth century. 
                        However, McManus has convincingly outlined why this identification is doubtful <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1945"
                            >(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1945">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">71</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. 
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#LAN2006"
                            ><bibl><author>Lankford</author> 
                                (<date when="2006">2006</date></bibl>)</ref> notes a possible reflex in the the genealogies: <hi rend="italic">Síl Faidloga</hi> (earlier <hi rend="italic">Fáithloga</hi>, *VATTI + *LUGO) 
                        but if this is the same name then a final vowel must have been omitted in the inscription. However, considering that the second G is right at the top corner of the vertical angle, 
                        it is possible that damage to the very top of the stone may have resulted in the loss of a notch or two.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p>In this inscription all endings are lost, including in the formula word 
                        (MAQ, earlier MAQ(Q)I) but syncope has not yet taken place (VATT<hi rend="bold">I</hi>LLOGG). This may 
                        suggest a date of approximately the <origDate notBefore="0550" notAfter="0600">second half of the sixth century</origDate> (<ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">96-7</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</p></item>
                </list>
                
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">built into a nineteenth-century burial vault or tomb in the south-west corner of the church in the townland of
                                <placeName type="townland">Ratass</placeName> and barony of
                            <placeName type="barony">Trughanacmy</placeName>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-9.681883, 52.267049</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">On site inside the church ruin at Ratass where it [along with the cross-slab] has been attached to the wall with a metal bracket. <ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KE029-157002-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>Discovered in 1975 during a routine clean-up of the interior of the ancient church at Ratass. 
                    </p>
            </div>
